article.description: Diana Taurasi made a career-high seven 3-pointers and scored 27 points to lead No. 5 Connecticut to a 72-47 win over Rutgers on Monday.
article.headline: Husky star makes career-high seven
article.story:
HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Diana Taurasi broke out of her three-game
shooting slump in a big way Monday.

Taurasi made a career-high seven 3-pointers and scored 27 points
in No. 5 Connecticut's 72-47 win over Rutgers on Monday.

The senior, who is now fifth on the all-time scoring list at
UConn with 1,876 points, was shooting 15-of-51 coming into the game
but found her touch quickly. She hit her first five shots and the
Huskies cruised against the banged-up Scarlet Knights.

"I was feeling good today," Taurasi said. "We were getting a
couple of bounces defensively and offensively, and when you shoot
and the shot goes in like that, it gives you confidence."

The Huskies (13-2, 4-1 Big East) also got a big boost from
reserve center Willnett Crockett, who finished with eight rebounds
and three blocks. The 6-foot-2 sophomore missed the first eight
games with an ankle injury and gave Rutgers matchup problems
inside.

"We're at our best when we have a good rotation out there that
includes Willnett," UConn coach Geno Auriemma said. "Willnett
changes the game when she's playing with a lot of energy. She's too
big, she's too quick and she's too strong for most people to
handle. All of a sudden our defense changes."

Rutgers (9-7, 2-3), which dressed just eight players, has
dropped three of its last four and is 3-4 against ranked opponents
this season. Cappie Pondexter led Rutgers with 13 points, but was
held to just four in the first half.

Rutgers has three players with shoulder injuries and starting
guard Chelsea Newton left the game late in the first half with a
bruised shin and did not return.

"We don't have a lot of players on the team in the first place
and when you get injuries, it makes a big difference," Rutgers
coach C. Vivian Stringer said. "You've got to go with what you
got. We played a great team."

UConn now holds a 15-1 in edge in the series.

Taurasi's slump included last week's 15-point loss at Notre
Dame, where she hit just 4-of-15 from the field.

"We've never seen Diana in a slump, so we kind of assume she
doesn't go through slumps," Auriemma said. "But she does, she's
just like everybody else. She's a worrier. She was overly concerned
with the rest of the guys on the team and what was going on. She
needed to clear her mind and worry about Diana and she did that
today."

Taurasi quickly found her touch against the Scarlet Knights,
hitting her first five shots and finished 10-of-15.

She took a breather with about five minutes to go in the first
half and her teammates never missed a beat, outscoring Rutgers 7-0
over a two-minute span. Taurasi re-entered and quickly hit her
fourth 3-pointer of the game, and UConn took a 40-17 halftime lead.
UConn led by as many as 35 in the second half.

The Scarlet Knights struggled from the floor, shooting just 33
percent in the game and were 3-of-13 from the free-throw line.

The Huskies were able to break the press early and dominated
inside with Crockett, who had seven boards and two blocks in her
first 10 minutes.

Crockett and her teammates knew Taurasi would get her touch back
sooner or later.

"(Diana) is always going to come out there and produce for
us," Crockett said. "She's going to have bad games, but when she
has bad games, they're good games for normal people. She came out
here and she stuck it too them."
